{"clauses":[{"item_alias":"K1","response":"The criticism misreads the standard. Clause (2) requires forbidden cases that are concrete observations which could realistically have obtained. The target provides exactly that: a specific paleoclimatic observation (normal precipitation in the Eastern Mediterranean, 1200–1150 BC) that would directly falsify the claimed mechanism of exogenous climatic forcing. The standard does not require separate forbidden cases for each region covered; it requires forbidden cases for the claim as stated. The claim's mechanism is a single climatic event affecting multiple regions, so a single paleoclimatic counterexample covering the relevant temporal and spatial domain is sufficient. The additional examples the criticism demands (grain storage levels, burial sites, administrative records) are downstream effects, not direct tests of the climatic mechanism itself, and the standard does not mandate forbidden cases at every link in the causal chain."}]}